n|2005\u20132007,<br>2009\u20132010,<br>2012, 2018\n|7 years winning both titles - Monte Carlo & Rome\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2008\n|Winner of [[2008 Masters Series Monte-Carlo \u2013 Singles|singles]] and [[2008 Masters Series Monte-Carlo \u2013 Doubles|doubles]] tournament at the same tournament and in the same year (Monte Carlo Masters)\n|[[Jim Courier]]\n|-\n|2011, 2013\n|5 consecutive finals\n|Novak Djokovic\n|-\n|2009\n|Reached quarter-finals, or better, in all 9 Masters 1000 events of the year\n|Novak Djokovic\n|-\n|2005, 2008, 2011, 2014, 2017\n|Miami - Five runner-up finishes at the same Masters 1000 event without winning a title.\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|}\n\n* [[Andy Murray]] accomplished this feat at the Australian Open by finishing runner-up 5 times without winning a title.\n* [[Novak Djokovic]] also reached the quarter-finals, or better, in all 9 Masters 1000 events of the year in 2009.  They met in 6 out of the 9 tournaments with each winning 3 of the matches.  Nadal prevailed in the Monte Carlo final, Madrid semi-final, and Rome final, while Djokovic bested him in the Cincinnati semi-final, Shanghai final, Paris semi-final, where he would go on to win the title.\n\n== Records at each ATP 500 Series & Masters 1000 tournaments ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Tournament \n!Year(s)\n!Record accomplished\n!Players tied\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |'''[[Monte Carlo Masters]]'''\n|2005\u20132012, 2016\u20132018\n||[[Monte-Carlo Masters#Singles|11 titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132012\n|[[Monte-Carlo Masters#Singles|8 consecutive titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2007-08, 2010, 2012, 2018\n||[[Monte-Carlo Masters#Singles|5 titles without dropping a set]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132013\n|[[Monte-Carlo Masters#Singles|9 consecutive finals]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132013, 2016\u20132018\n|[[Monte-Carlo Masters#Singles|12 finals overall]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132013\n|[[Rafael Nadal's 46-match winning streak at the Monte-Carlo Masters|46 Match win streak]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Italian Open (tennis)|'''Italian Open (Rome)''']]\n|2005\u20132007, 2009\u20132010, 2012\u20132013, 2018, 2019\n|[[Italian Open (tennis)#Men|9 titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132007, 2009\u20132014, 2018, 2019\n|[[Italian Open (tennis)#Men|11 finals overall]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2009\u20132014\n|[[Italian Open (tennis)#Men|6 consecutive finals]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005\u20132007\n|[[Italian Open (tennis)#Men|3 consecutive titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Madrid Open (tennis)|'''Madrid Open''']]                 \n|2005 <small>(hard)</small>, 2010, 2013\u20132014, 2017<!-- Nadal won the 2005 Madrid Open title on hard courts.  The 2008 title was the Hamburg Open on clay, which was renamed the Madrid Open in 2009...at the same time, the Shanghai Open started in 2009 and took the place of the Madrid Open on hard courts...which is why the Madrid Open has only been played on clay since 2009.  If you go to the [[Madrid Open (tennis)]] site you'll see Nadal's named listed as the 2005 champion, and if you go to [[German Open Tennis Championships]] you'll see Nadal was the 2008 champion. Also note that it's now an ATP500 level event. -->\n|[[Madrid Open (tennis)#Men's singles|5 titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|[[Madrid Open (tennis)#Men's singles|2 consecutive titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005 <small>(indoor hard)</small>, 2009\u201311, 2013\u201315, 2017\n|[[Madrid Open (tennis)#Men's singles|8 finals overall]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2009\u20132011 & 2013\u20132015\n|[[Madrid Open (tennis)#Men's singles|3 consecutive finals]]<!-- it wasn't 5 consecutive from 2007 to 2011 as the 2007 & 2008 finals were the Hamburg Open. His most consecutive were 3, and he accomplished it twice, in 2009-2011 and 2013-2015.  -->                                                         \n|'''Stands alone'''   \n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |[[Barcelona Open (tennis)|'''Barcelona Open''']]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2005\u20132009, 2011\u20132013, 2016\u20132018\n|[[Barcelona Open (tennis)#Winner of most singles titles|11 titles]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|[[Barcelona Open (tennis)#Most singles finals|11 finals]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|Undefeated in eleven finals (11-0)\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|[[Three-peat|3 three-peats]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2005-2009\n|5 consecutive titles\n|'''Stands alone''' \n|-\n|2005, 2007, 2009, 2011-13, 2016-18\n|9 titles without dropping a set\n|'''Stands alone''' \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Mexican Open (tennis)|'''Acapulco Open''']]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2005, 2013, 2017, 2020\n|3 titles without dropping a set\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|14 consecutive match wins\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|28 consecutive sets won\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|-\n \n|}\n* Nadal was the first player to win 25 Masters 1000 titles in the Open Era, he surpassed Ivan Lendl's record of 22 in 2013. Nadal was also the first player to win 35 Masters 1000 titles in 2019.\n\n== Rankings records and achievements ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Time span\n!Record or achievement accomplished\n!Player tied\n|-\n| 2008-2019\n|Only man to have regained the year-end No. 1 crown four times<ref name=\"atpworldtour.com\">https://www.atptour.com/en/news/nadal-clinches-2019-year-end-no-1-atp-rankings . Retrieved 14 November 2019.</ref>\n| '''Stands alone'''\n|-\n| 2008-2019\n|11 years - Longest gap between first year-end No. 1 finish (2008) and his most recent year-end No. 1 finish (2019)<ref name=\"atpworldtour.com\"/>\n| '''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2008-2019\n|Only male player to finish year-end No. 1 five times in non-consecutive years<ref>https://www.atptour.com/en/news/nadal-clinches-2019-year-end-no-1-atp-rankings . Retrieved 14 November 2019.</ref>\n| '''Stands alone'''\n|-\n|2013-2017\n|Only male player to finish year-end No. 1 4+ years since the last time he finished year-end No. 1<ref name=\"atpworldtour.com\"/>\n| '''Stands a